text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Language Discrimination towards Job Applicants%0a:Author: Abi_S%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 30.04.2021 - 16:10%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-223024-466030#%0a* [-11.05.2021 - 15:30-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-223024-466030#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-223021-464110#%0a----%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-11.05.2021 - 15:30-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!TA_mason%0anice write-up! %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210511-223021-464110 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210511-223021-464110#%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn my wiki posting, I'm focusing on blatant language discrimination towards job applicants, evident in job postings or requirements%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aArticle: https://truthbetold.news/2020/01/is-it-the-way-i-talk-hiring-discrimination-based-on-an-accent-is-illegal/%0a%0aThe article points out that there are postings on popular job or networking sites, such as LinkedIn or Monster, where companies in the US blatantly have "no accent" as a requirement. In this circumstance, they are criticizing most dialects that are not standard American English. %0a%0aThe article interviews other employees with "accents", as they talk about how having an accent ties into their identity, of who they are and their history. Moreover, it also explores the issue of the concept of an accent. An accent to Americans is not identical to what's considered an accent to people internationally. This may imply accents as something that may play a role in terms of power and status. %0a%0aDifferent dialects aren't ungrammatical, and aren't perceived as ungrammatical, but more of the fact that dialects also tie people to stereotypes - like being uneducated. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
